    {
      "id": "2lQArGE6BWEBqLp1aOtEk",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 1556.4285714285713,
      "y": 1337.2222222222224,
      "width": 1526.6190185546875,
      "height": 1525,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "au",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 460111929,
      "version": 4,
      "versionNonce": 838734167,
      "isDeleted": true,
      "boundElements": null,
      "updated": 1775513052814,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Your summary is **mostly correct**, but I’ll clarify and tighten a few points for accuracy and interview polish:\n\n---\n\n### **1️⃣ Database with ACID + locking**\n\n✅ Correct.\n\n* Using a database like **PostgreSQL, MySQL (InnoDB)**, or any transactional DB with **row-level locks** ensures:\n\n  * Atomicity: deposit + transaction insert happen together\n  * Consistency: balances remain correct\n  * Isolation: concurrent updates serialize automatically\n  * Durability: committed updates persist\n\n* No external lock service is needed.\n\n---\n\n### **2️⃣ Database without ACID + locking**\n\n✅ Partially correct, but needs nuance.\n\n* **Optimistic concurrency control (OCC) / versioning** can help detect conflicts (`version` or `updated_at`).\n\n  * If two updates happen at the same time, the one with an outdated version **fails and retries**.\n  * Guarantees **eventual consistency**, not strict immediate consistency.\n\n* **Distributed systems**: Using **Redis distributed locks (Redlock)** or another centralized lock service ensures **mutual exclusion across app servers**.\n\n> Key: OCC alone doesn’t prevent race conditions in distributed systems unless you combine it with some **coordination**.\n\n---\n\n### **3️⃣ ACID DB + multiple app servers**\n\n✅ Mostly correct, but needs precision.\n\n* **Sharding**: partition users/accounts so that each shard handles a subset → ensures updates on a shard are local and serializable.\n\n  * Replicate shards for **failover**.\n\n* **Single master DB**: all writes go to **one leader node**, reads can go to replicas.\n\n  * Leader ensures **consistency**, replicas can lag slightly (eventual consistency for reads).\n\n* **Note**: If you have multiple shards or multiple leaders, you may need **distributed transactions (2PC or consensus protocols)**.\n\n---\n\n### **Minor polish for interview**\n\n1. Mention **row-level locks** explicitly for ACID DB.\n2. For OCC, emphasize **retry mechanism** after version mismatch.\n3. For distributed Redis locks, mention **TTL and ownership key** to avoid deadlocks.\n4. For multi-app-server + multi-DB, clearly separate **sharding** vs **leader-based single DB** approaches.\n\n---\n\nIf you want, I can rewrite your **summary in a clean, 1-minute interview-ready version** — concise and technically precise. Do you want me to do that?\n",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Your summary is **mostly correct**, but I’ll clarify and tighten a few points for accuracy and interview polish:\n\n---\n\n### **1️⃣ Database with ACID + locking**\n\n✅ Correct.\n\n* Using a database like **PostgreSQL, MySQL (InnoDB)**, or any transactional DB with **row-level locks** ensures:\n\n  * Atomicity: deposit + transaction insert happen together\n  * Consistency: balances remain correct\n  * Isolation: concurrent updates serialize automatically\n  * Durability: committed updates persist\n\n* No external lock service is needed.\n\n---\n\n### **2️⃣ Database without ACID + locking**\n\n✅ Partially correct, but needs nuance.\n\n* **Optimistic concurrency control (OCC) / versioning** can help detect conflicts (`version` or `updated_at`).\n\n  * If two updates happen at the same time, the one with an outdated version **fails and retries**.\n  * Guarantees **eventual consistency**, not strict immediate consistency.\n\n* **Distributed systems**: Using **Redis distributed locks (Redlock)** or another centralized lock service ensures **mutual exclusion across app servers**.\n\n> Key: OCC alone doesn’t prevent race conditions in distributed systems unless you combine it with some **coordination**.\n\n---\n\n### **3️⃣ ACID DB + multiple app servers**\n\n✅ Mostly correct, but needs precision.\n\n* **Sharding**: partition users/accounts so that each shard handles a subset → ensures updates on a shard are local and serializable.\n\n  * Replicate shards for **failover**.\n\n* **Single master DB**: all writes go to **one leader node**, reads can go to replicas.\n\n  * Leader ensures **consistency**, replicas can lag slightly (eventual consistency for reads).\n\n* **Note**: If you have multiple shards or multiple leaders, you may need **distributed transactions (2PC or consensus protocols)**.\n\n---\n\n### **Minor polish for interview**\n\n1. Mention **row-level locks** explicitly for ACID DB.\n2. For OCC, emphasize **retry mechanism** after version mismatch.\n3. For distributed Redis locks, mention **TTL and ownership key** to avoid deadlocks.\n4. For multi-app-server + multi-DB, clearly separate **sharding** vs **leader-based single DB** approaches.\n\n---\n\nIf you want, I can rewrite your **summary in a clean, 1-minute interview-ready version** — concise and technically precise. Do you want me to do that?\n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "06Mj78wVpUzv3tL8Rt5Jc",
