      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "\n\nUsing a database like PostgreSQL, MySQL (InnoDB), or any transactional DB with row-level locks ensures:\nAtomicity: deposit + transaction insert happen together\nConsistency: balances remain correct\nIsolation: concurrent updates serialize automatically\nDurability: committed updates persist\nNo external lock service is needed.\n\nDatabase without ACID + locking\n\nPartially correct, but needs nuance.\n\nOptimistic concurrency control (OCC) / versioning can help detect conflicts (version or updated_at).\nIf two updates happen at the same time, the one with an outdated version fails and retries.\nGuarantees eventual consistency, not strict immediate consistency.\nDistributed systems: Using Redis distributed locks (Redlock) or another centralized lock service ensures mutual exclusion across app servers.\n\nKey: OCC alone doesn’t prevent race conditions in distributed systems unless you combine it with some coordination.\n\nACID DB + multiple app servers\n\nSharding: partition users/accounts so that each shard handles a subset → ensures updates on a shard are local and serializable.\nReplicate shards for failover.\nSingle master DB: all writes go to one leader node, reads can go to replicas.\nLeader ensures consistency, replicas can lag slightly (eventual consistency for reads).\nNote: If you have multiple shards or multiple leaders, you may need distributed transactions (2PC or consensus protocols).",
      "fontSize": 20,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "\n\nUsing a database like PostgreSQL, MySQL (InnoDB), or any transactional DB with row-level locks ensures:\nAtomicity: deposit + transaction insert happen together\nConsistency: balances remain correct\nIsolation: concurrent updates serialize automatically\nDurability: committed updates persist\nNo external lock service is needed.\n\nDatabase without ACID + locking\n\nPartially correct, but needs nuance.\n\nOptimistic concurrency control (OCC) / versioning can help detect conflicts (version or updated_at).\nIf two updates happen at the same time, the one with an outdated version fails and retries.\nGuarantees eventual consistency, not strict immediate consistency.\nDistributed systems: Using Redis distributed locks (Redlock) or another centralized lock service ensures mutual exclusion across app servers.\n\nKey: OCC alone doesn’t prevent race conditions in distributed systems unless you combine it with some coordination.\n\nACID DB + multiple app servers\n\nSharding: partition users/accounts so that each shard handles a subset → ensures updates on a shard are local and serializable.\nReplicate shards for failover.\nSingle master DB: all writes go to one leader node, reads can go to replicas.\nLeader ensures consistency, replicas can lag slightly (eventual consistency for reads).\nNote: If you have multiple shards or multiple leaders, you may need distributed transactions (2PC or consensus protocols).",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
